Concept, design and implementation

Concept

The basic concept of the LANLord is that it is a server that hosts an OS image with a bunch of games and customization that other computers will boot from across a network.

This is roughly similar to what we used to call "mainframe computing" back in ye olden days, except that it isn't a "mainframe" in the traditional sense; it is more akin to a "miniframe".  The difference is typically with a mainframe computer, the mainframe does all the heavy-lifting/computing and just sends display information to terminals connected to it. The terminals have just enough hardware to run a monitor and a keyboard/interface with the mainframe. The LANLord is more of a hybrid approach or a "miniframe" where the server hosts an image that other real computers (like desktops, laptops etc.) will use to boot into an operating system. This leverages the actual hardware of the client computers instead of putting the entire load on the server, thus vastly reducing the cost of building/running the server and allowing damn-near any type of computer to be used with the LANLord. Additionally, it reduces the amount of network traffic that must travel back-and-forth from the LANLord and each client in contrast to the mainframe style.

Design

Operating System & Software

Operating System

The LANLord is a standard install of LMDE 6 (Linux Mint Debian Edition).

Why LMDE? For one, Linux Mint has proven to be the best Linux distribution for people unfamiliar/slightly familiar with computers for the following reasons:

  • Debian-based
  • User-friendly layout
  • Windows XP-esque design
  • No non-sense navigation/minimal clutter

The underlying OS is not-so-much important (besides being something based on Debian), but the desktop environment is. In early versions of the LANStick/LANLord, XFCE and KDE were used. Both were for the most part perfectly functional, but the user experience was lacking/confusing for your average user. Both desktops by the end were heavily-modified versions of what comes out-of-the-box and were very cool looking, but were also a buggy/unstable mess. Cinnamon turned out to be the overall best option and requires very little tweaking and what tweaks there are can be copied to different users easily with a dconf file.

The choice between regular Linux Mint and LMDE is fairly ambiguous regarding benefit and truth be told, it should probably be regular Linux Mint over LMDE. LMDE was chosen as it was initally believed we could have rock-solid stability and have all the latest bells and whistles added to Cinnamon when they are released. This part is true, but being Debian based (Debian 12 at the time of writing) there have been a few hiccups that simply don't exist with regular, Ubuntu-based Mint.

It is likely the LANLord's OS will be changed to regular Linux Mint in the future

Software

LTSP

The LANLord is made possible with the use of LTSP (Linux Server Terminal Project)

LTSP is more-or-less a collection of scripts that leverage existing programs for the end goal of distributed computing in educational environments (for our purposes, LAN parties...). Clients boot an operating system image through PXE booting ("pixie" booting), and grab whatever filesystem information they need over NFS post-boot. A rough breakdown of how it does this is as follows:

  • LTSP creates a bootable image from the OS it's installed on
  • LTSP uses dnsmasq for either dhcp-proxy or a real DHCP server to give clients boot information
  • Clients configured to PXE boot will reach out to the network/DHCP server for PXE information
  • After getting PXE information, clients receive a compressed linux kernel with NFS mount information for the operating system they will be running
  • Client boots into OS 

This for the most part automagically works, but there are a handful of caveats such as:

  • The client CPU must be x86 64-bit architecture (or amd64 in Linux lingo). This means most home computers from the last ~10-15 years. 32-bit machines will NOT work
  • The client must have an Ethernet port. The traditional RJ-45 jack that is virtually on every desktop but is likely to not be included on laptops (although there are plenty of exceptions, especially with older laptops). PXE booting over WiFi is NOT an option, unfortunately.
  • If the client was e-waste when it was built, it is still e-waste today. The primary function of the LANLord is to play games, specifically 3D games. So it needs to be at least competent at playing 3D games from around 2000-2005 to have a fun experience. Upgrades/sprucing up may be required (and is usually extremely cheap to do, so keep that in mind).

Hardware

The LANLord is designed to be "portable". Portable meaning that it is a couple of 3U servers, a 1U switch and a 1U network switch mounted into 8U roll-around audio-equipment case. It's meant to be wheeled to a central location, and then Ethernet cables ran from clients back to the LANLord. The LANLord can be plugged into an existing network, however this is not required and is designed to be it's own network when no others are available.

The LANLord altogether is made-up of five components (listed from top-to-bottom):

  • Power Distribution Unit
  • The LANBaron
    • Support server: Another Debian server that hosts various game servers, documentation, and other services that facilitate the playing of video games
  • Brush panel
    • A passthrough for Ethernet and fiber-optic cables to plug into the network switch
  • TP-Link TL-SG3428X Switch
    • Network switch: Gigabit network switch with four SFP+ ports. Two ports are occupied by the LANBaron and LANLord
  • LANLord (server)
    • The star of the show. Primary server that distributes the LMDE image to clients. Connected to the TP-Link switch via
    • SFP+ fiber LC.

LANLord (server)

The LANLord server uses your typical off-the-shelf PC hardware, enterprise-grade gear need not apply. Components include:

  • Gigabyte B550M AM4 Motherboard
  • AMD Ryzen 3 2200G
  • Silicon Power 16 GB 2400MT/s DDR4 RAM
  • WD_BLACK SN770 500GB NVMe SSD
    • Mounted as /

  • Crucial P3 Plus 2TB NVMe SSD

    • Mounted as /srv
  • Sabrent SB-ROCKET 1TB NVMe SSD
    • Mounted as /mnt/games
  • 3 x Seagate IronWolf Pro 4TB HDD (RAID 5)
    • Mounted as /mnt/lanserfs-home

Implementation

Through much trial-and-error, this is how I've settled (so far) on how to assemble and operate the LANLord. Improvement is always needed, and is desired

Filesystem & Mountpoints

The filesystem layout plays an important part in how the LANLord operates. This is not a set-in-stone idea, it's just what was thought to work best for handling potentially tens of clients. Below is how disks are mounted and why:

  • /dev/md127
    • 3 x Seagate IronWolf Pro 4TB HDD
      • RAID 5 made up of /dev/sda,/dev/sdb,/dev/sdc
        • Mounted at /mnt/lanserfs-home
          • This is for users' /home directories. In practice this is a way for a user to store files/data back onto the LANLord for long-term storage
  • /dev/nvme0n1p1
    • WD_BLACK SN770 500GB NVMe SSD
      • Root filesystem
  • /dev/nvme1n1p1
    • Crucial P3 Plus 2TB NVMe SSD
      • Mounted at /srv.
        • This is where the LTSP image that is served to clients is stored. The drive needs to be large, as the LTSP image is quite large, but also by default keeps the previous version of the image. This means that whatever image you make is stored twice. This drive is an NVMe drive because speed is important, the image needs to be served as fast the network can serve
  • /dev/nvme2n1p1
    • Sabrent SB-ROCKET 1TB NVMe SSD
      • Mounted as /mnt/games
        • This could be on a hard drive, but was placed on it's own NVMe SSD for speed during image capturing and to reduce wear and tear on the NVMe that hosts the LTSP image

Administrators, Users & Desktop customizations

Administrator

The administrator for the LANLord is lanmaster, it is the only admin account

lanmaster has sudo privilege and is the only member part of the epoptes group, see the Epoptes section further below for details

Epoptes

During deployment of LANLord as it is the only one that is part of the epoptes group. Epoptes is the program that shows the screen of all connected client computers and gives the administrator some options to control their sessions. This can Wake-On-LAN clients that have their MAC addresses listed

Users

When a client computer boots from LANLord, they are presented with the regular LightDM display manager and a text field where they need to specify which user they would like to login to

Users cannot make their own users and need to know of a user that already exists. If they wish to have their own unique user, the administrator will need to create one for them

User desktop customization

To provide a fun and uniform experience for all users, the Cinnamon Desktop has a few customizations applied to it by modifying a test-user's  that are taken from dconf and stored into a file. A set of wallpapers set to randomly rotate, and custom sounds are set to play during login and logout. Shortcut icons for the Menu and Desktop as well as Autostart files are also included. These files are copied to the user upon user creation.  This is done by simply storing these files in their respective directories

These files are stored in:

 /etc/skel
